                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d415">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890G.24/58: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister Resident in Iraq</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baghdad</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-17T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 17, 1942—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>240. Reference my No. 226, October 8, 1 p.m. Department may defer for the present
                    sending wording of draft agreement mentioned in that message. With the
                    approaching November opening of Parliament the situation gives promise of
                    changing. Further discussions with British financial adviser indicate a
                    possibility that Iraqi Government may undertake to pass legislation without
                    further action by us. Nuri Pasha has been in Egypt for past week but returns in
                    next few days. Will keep you advised of developments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
